I've been in biology for eight months now, and I've experienced many emotions: the awe of watching neurons talk to each under the microscope; the irritation of dropping my gel on the floor; the pride of understanding a biology process at the chemical level. Above all, there's the occasional recurring dread: did I enter biology too early to answer the questions I really want to?

In biology, there's an overwhelming about that people know, and an even more overwhelming amount that no one actually knows (even if they think they do). 
Why does biology feel so slow? 
